Doc Spatz,<br><br>
Thank you for your candor. <br><br>
My purpose is to further understanding. We all are able to concur that NEVER should there be another Vietnam.<br><br>
It is not hard for me to realize that had the war been justifiable, ie there had REALLY been a threat to our nation's security, it would not have been so widely protested. <br><br>
The voice of fear and terror was in our ears. We, as young men, weighed that voice and attempted to balance it with whether or not the war was right or wrong. When the young woman on the airplane asked why I was going, I distinctly remember my saying that I didn't want to go to jail! I could not say that I agreed with the policy of the United States.<br><br>
Contrast this with those who fought in WWII!<br><br>
You will find that many of the hawkish of the hawks have a grudging respect for those who chose jail. Isn't it funny how things change in 30 years? BUT! It took 30 years of sincere thought. AND! It takes a realization that we, who served in Vietnam, were very much fucked over. <br><br>

